article.headline: Iowa State 70, Savannah State 59
article.story: AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Rahshon Clark scored 16 points and Wesley Johnson had 15 points and 11 rebounds as Iowa State broke a three-game losing streak with a 70-59 victory over Savannah State on Wednesday night. Mike Taylor, Iowa State's leading scorer for the season, struggled most of the night after getting two early fouls, but he hit a key 3-pointer to help the Cyclones (7-3) finally shake their feisty opponent and hand the Tigers (5-8) their eighth straight loss. Joseph Flegler kept Savannah State close with his outside shooting and finished with 22 points, going 8-for-12 from the field with four 3-pointers. Joshua Obiajunwa added 13 points and Patrick Hardy 12 for the Tigers, who trailed just 55-53 after Flegler hit a long 3 from the right wing with 4:28 left. But Savannah State made only one shot over the next 3½ minutes and Iowa State opened some breathing room. Taylor sank two free throws to make it 57-53, then hit a 3 from the right side for a 60-53 lead with 3:37 to play. After that, the Cyclones just had to make their free throws, and they did, hitting 10 of 12 to wrap it up. The 3 was Taylor's only basket of the game. He didn't score until making two free throws with 11:49 remaining and finished with eight points, half his average. Iowa State coach Greg McDermott juggled his lineup to try to shake things up, giving Dodie Dunson and Cory Johnson their first starts of the season, and the Cyclones promptly fell behind 6-0. They got back in it by scoring the next seven points but could never get enough defensive stops to put their lightly regarded opponent away. Iowa State appeared to be taking control when it ran off eight straight points midway through the opening half to erase a 14-13 Savannah State lead. The Cyclones haven't gotten much inside scoring this season, but all four of their baskets in that run came from in close. Clark hit two straight layups, Jiri Hubalek worked his way inside for a bucket and Hubalek followed up his own miss to make it 21-14. Four times Iowa State got its lead up to eight, but Savannah State made some tough shots and kept coming back. Flegler hit a 3-pointer with the shot clock about to expire to cut the lead to five and later hit back-to-back 3s to leave the Tigers trailing 34-32 at the half. Iowa State's Jessan Gray left the game late in the first half with a broken nose and did not return.
